    <h2>1. Commercial Vegetable Cutting Machines: Dice, Slice, Shred & Julienne</h2>

    <p>A commercial vegetable cutting machine is the centerpiece of any professional kitchen's prep area. These machines replace the work of multiple kitchen staff members, processing vegetables into uniform cuts at high speed. The consistency they deliver is impossible to achieve by hand — every slice is the same thickness, every dice is the same size, and every julienne strip is identical. This consistency translates directly into more predictable cooking times, better presentation, and reduced food waste.</p>

    <h3>Types of Commercial Vegetable Cutters</h3>

    <p><strong>Continuous-Feed Vegetable Cutters:</strong> These are the workhorses of commercial vegetable processing. Vegetables are fed into a hopper at the top, pass through a rotating cutting disc, and exit from the bottom or side in the desired cut. Continuous-feed cutters can process 50–500 kg of vegetables per hour depending on the model and the vegetable being processed. They are ideal for kitchens that need to process large volumes — hotel banquet kitchens, central commissary kitchens, large restaurants, and catering operations.</p>

    <p><strong>Combination Vegetable Cutters (Cutter-Mixers):</strong> These machines combine a continuous-feed cutter with a bowl cutter/mixer function. You can slice, dice, and shred vegetables using the continuous-feed attachment, and also chop, puree, emulsify, and mix using the bowl function. Machines like the Robot Coupe R301 Ultra and R401 are popular examples. These are excellent for kitchens with limited space that need multi-function capability.</p>

    <p><strong>Table-Top Vegetable Cutters (Indian-Made):</strong> Several Indian manufacturers produce simpler, more affordable vegetable cutters designed specifically for the Indian market. These are typically single-function machines — an onion slicer, a vegetable dicer, or a chips cutter. They are less versatile than European continuous-feed cutters but significantly cheaper, and they get the job done for smaller operations.</p>

