    <h2>2. Commercial Onion Cutting Machine: Prices & Types</h2>

    <p>In Indian commercial kitchens, the single vegetable that consumes the most prep time is the onion. A typical North Indian restaurant serving 200 covers per day uses 30–50 kg of onions daily — all of which need to be peeled and chopped, sliced, or diced. That is hours of tearful, repetitive labour every single day. A commercial onion cutting machine eliminates this bottleneck entirely.</p>

    <h3>Types of Commercial Onion Cutters</h3>

    <p><strong>Onion Slicer Machines:</strong> These produce uniform onion slices (rings or half-rings) at speeds of 50–200 kg/hr. They are essential for restaurants that serve large quantities of onion rings, salads, or biryanis where sliced onions are needed. Most onion slicers can also handle other round vegetables like tomatoes and potatoes.</p>

    <p><strong>Onion Chopper/Dicer Machines:</strong> These cut onions into small, uniform pieces — the kind you need for gravies, curries, and sauteing. They are the more common requirement in Indian kitchens. Good onion dicers can process 50–300 kg/hr depending on the size and type of machine.</p>

    <p><strong>Multi-Function Vegetable Cutters with Onion Capability:</strong> Most continuous-feed vegetable cutters (discussed in Section 1) can handle onions with the right disc. If you already own or plan to buy a Robot Coupe or Hallde vegetable cutter, you may not need a separate onion machine. However, dedicated onion cutters are often preferred in high-volume Indian kitchens because they can be set up once and left to process onions all morning without needing disc changes.</p>

