    <h2>4. Potato Chips & Wafer Slicing Machines</h2>

    <p>India has a massive market for potato chips, wafers, and french fries — both in restaurants and as a standalone snack business. Potato chips slicing machines are specialized equipment designed to produce thin, uniform slices at high speed. They range from simple hand-cranked mandoline-style cutters to fully automatic continuous slicing lines.</p>

    <h3>Types of Potato Chips Slicers</h3>

    <p><strong>Manual Potato Slicer / Mandoline (Commercial Grade):</strong> A heavy-duty mandoline with adjustable thickness. Suitable for small-volume operations — street food stalls, small cafes, or restaurants that make chips as a side dish rather than a main product. Output: 10–30 kg/hr. Price: ₹2,000–₹10,000.</p>

    <p><strong>Electric Potato Chips Slicer (Indian-Made):</strong> A motorized slicer with a rotating blade disc. Potatoes are pushed through a feed tube against the rotating blade, producing uniform slices. Output: 50–150 kg/hr. Price: ₹15,000–₹60,000. These are popular with small to mid-size chips manufacturing businesses.</p>

    <p><strong>Automatic Potato Chips Line (Slicer + Washer):</strong> A combined machine that slices potatoes and washes the starch off the slices in a single pass. Essential for chips manufacturing where starch removal determines the crispiness of the final product. Output: 100–500 kg/hr. Price: ₹80,000–₹3,00,000.</p>

    <p><strong>French Fry Cutters:</strong> These cut potatoes into uniform strips for french fries. Available as manual lever-operated (₹3,000–₹8,000), semi-automatic (₹15,000–₹40,000), and fully automatic (₹50,000–₹2,00,000) models. Most continuous-feed vegetable cutters can also cut french fries with the right grid attachment.</p>

    <p>If chips or fries are a significant part of your menu, a dedicated slicer or cutter pays for itself quickly. For a broader understanding of food business setup costs, see our <a href="/blog/restaurant-setup-cost-india">restaurant setup cost guide</a>.</p>

    <h2>5. Commercial Food Processors: Bowl Cutters & Vertical Cutters</h2>

    <p>A commercial food processor is different from a vegetable cutter. While a vegetable cutter produces defined cuts (slices, dices, julienne), a food processor chops, purees, mixes, kneads, and emulsifies using a blade that rotates inside a bowl. Commercial food processors are essential for making dips, sauces, chutneys, marinades, doughs, and any preparation that requires ingredients to be broken down rather than cut into neat shapes.</p>

    <h3>Bowl Cutters (Cutter-Mixers)</h3>

    <p>A bowl cutter — also called a cutter-mixer or vertical cutter — has a stainless steel bowl with a rotating blade at the bottom. Ingredients are loaded into the bowl, the lid is closed, and the blade processes them to the desired consistency. Bowl sizes range from 2.5 litres (small table-top models) to 20+ litres (large floor-standing units).</p>

