    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h3>Common Questions About Commercial Vegetable Cutting Machines</h3>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a commercial vegetable cutting machine in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Commercial vegetable cutting machine prices in India range from ₹15,000 for a basic Indian-made vegetable cutter to over ₹8,50,000 for a heavy-duty European continuous-feed processor like the Robot Coupe CL60. For most restaurants, a machine in the ₹35,000–₹2,00,000 range provides the best value. The price depends on brand (Indian vs European), motor power, throughput capacity, and the number of cutting discs included.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Which brand is best for commercial vegetable cutting machines in India? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Robot Coupe (France) is the global industry standard and the most widely recommended brand for commercial vegetable cutting machines. Their CL Series vegetable cutters and R-Series food processors are used in professional kitchens worldwide. Hallde (Sweden) and Dito Sama (France/Italy) are excellent alternatives. For budget-conscious buyers, Indian manufacturers offer practical solutions at 30–50% of European prices, though with shorter lifespans and less versatility.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How much does a commercial onion cutting machine cost? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>A commercial onion cutting machine costs between ₹3,000 for a manual lever-type chopper and ₹2,50,000 for a heavy-duty European electric onion processor. Most Indian restaurants find an electric onion slicer or dicer in the ₹25,000–₹60,000 range meets their needs. If you already own a continuous-feed vegetable cutter, it can likely handle onions with the right disc attachment, eliminating the need for a separate machine.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">What is the price of a commercial potato peeler machine? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>A commercial potato peeler machine costs between ₹20,000 for a 5 kg batch model and ₹1,50,000 for a 20–30 kg heavy-duty unit. The most popular size for restaurants is a 10 kg batch peeler, priced at ₹35,000–₹60,000. These abrasive drum peelers can process 120–150 kg of potatoes per hour and also work for carrots, beetroot, and other root vegetables.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Can one machine handle all vegetable cutting needs? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>A combination food processor with a continuous-feed attachment (like the Robot Coupe R301 Ultra or R401) can handle most vegetable cutting, chopping, pureeing, and mixing tasks in a single machine. However, it cannot replace a dedicated potato peeler or a high-volume onion cutter. For small to mid-size restaurants, a combination machine plus a potato peeler covers 90% of vegetable processing needs.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How long do commercial vegetable cutting machines last? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Premium European machines (Robot Coupe, Hallde) last 10–15+ years with proper maintenance. Indian-made machines typically last 3–7 years. The difference comes down to motor quality, bearing construction, blade materials, and overall build quality. Cutting discs need sharpening every 3–6 months and replacement every 2–3 years depending on usage volume.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">Do vegetable cutting machines need three-phase power? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Most small to mid-range commercial vegetable cutting machines (up to 1.5 HP) run on standard single-phase 220V power — the same supply available in all commercial kitchens. Machines above 1.5 HP typically require three-phase 440V power. Always check the electrical specification before purchasing. If your kitchen only has single-phase power, budget for a three-phase connection if you plan to buy heavy-duty equipment.</p></div>
      </div>

      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-q">How do I calculate the ROI of a commercial vegetable cutting machine? <span class="icon">+</span></button>
        <div class="faq-a"><p>Calculate the hours your kitchen staff currently spend on manual vegetable prep, multiply by their hourly wage, and compare against the machine cost. Most mid-size restaurants (200 covers/day) can save one full prep cook position (₹12,000–₹15,000/month) by investing in a vegetable cutter and potato peeler. A typical payback period is 8–15 months, after which the savings go directly to your profit.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

